tags: #TransTakeover #TransAwarenessWeek #tdor Boxing is more than a sport. I donâ€™t know who I would be if I hadnâ€™t wandered into a gym as a miserable teenager. I have been able to see the world, have a positive impact on my community, gained friends and family...but there are many who donâ€™t want trans athletes to be a part of the athletic world. Despite all the misinformation, trans athletes want the same as every athlete: a chance to participate and grow with the sport they love. We canâ€™t fight this battle alone and fortunately we donâ€™t have to. @AthleteAlly works to dismantle the structures of oppression that isolate, exclude and endanger LGBTQI+ people in sport, especially trans and nonbinary youth. In the past year, 19 states in the US have introduced horrific legislation targeting trans youth and their ability to play sports simply because of who they are.Â Â  Because of COVID-19, LGBTQI+ youth are at increased risk of depression, anxiety and suicidal thoughts. Sports are proven to reduce depression for LGBTQI+ youth. All athletes, and especially trans youth, deserve life-saving access to sports. Join Athlete Ally and help us fight to make sports welcoming for all. #TDOR #PROTECTTRANSYOUTH

#TransTakeover #TransAwarenessWeek #tdor [Content Warning: child sexual abuse] Iâ€™m not a survivor of child sexual abuse, but so many of my loved ones are. Since 20% of Americans are survivors, you or someone you know has lived through this violence. And if youâ€™re a transgender or gender non-conforming child, according to the American Academy of Pediatrics, youâ€™re more at risk of being targeted. My partner founded @mirror.memoirs so that transgender, non-binary, intersex and queer survivors of color have a place to share their stories, find healing community, and organize together to end rape culture. And they welcome the involvement of ANYONE who wants to live in a world without child sexual abuse. If you are in crisis and need immediate help, you can contact @trevorproject 24/7 toll-free hotline via phone (866-488-7386) or text START to 678-678 to access a confidential counselor. Trevor Project counselors are specifically trained to support LGBTQ young people under 25.

Yesterday I had surgery for my endometriosis â¤ï¸ Not a very glamorous post but I felt like I needed to share this to create more awareness around this disease. Endometriosis is a condition where tissue from the uterine lining decides to grow in other random parts of your body, causing pain. This can interfere with fertility and overall health and honestly - happiness.Â Â To top things off it is excruciatingly painful but nearly impossible to see through an ultrasound (unless you have endometrioma/chocolate cysts on your ovaries- thatâ€™s what I had). I have been in agony for years around my period and I was misdiagnosed countless times by doctors. â€œJust take Tylenol every dayâ€ â€œultrasound looks normal,â€ â€œ I think you just need to rest more, periods are always uncomfortable for people,â€ etc. I know a lot of people out there in the Endo community are familiar with these diagnoses which is why I am so passionate about this. Painful periods are not normal!!! I want to say thank you to @drvilasagar_endosurgeon and the amazing hospital staff at @atriumhealth who took care of me. You guys were literally angels to me and I am so grateful. To anyone out there who has endometriosis, I understand the depression, and overall loneliness that can occur with a conditionÂ Â that is so painful yet so hard to be interpreted by other people outside of the body. Itâ€™s hard when chronic pain is not validated and you donâ€™t get an answer or understanding. To my Endo warriors, I will continue to spread more awareness around endometriosis so that your symptoms can be validated. You are not alone and you are so strong !!!!

There are so many cool jobs on a set outside of being the actor on film.Thereâ€™s the Director of Photography that makes sure our shots and lighting look perfect. (our DP on ALICE also worked on WATCHMEN, heâ€™s truly incredible to watch and learn from.)Thereâ€™s the continuity person that literally watches for mistakes like someoneâ€™s hair was in front when it was supposed to be behind. Thereâ€™s the sound engineer who makes sure the mixes sound good on set as well as the boom operator thatâ€™s up close holding a lower mic for extra support during scenes. (The mics are heavy btw and some scenes are really long!)You have the PAâ€™s who make sure everyone is where they need to be, they are assistants to production. You also have camera asstâ€™s that mark where you are supposed to walk to ensure shot accuracy. And assist the camera operator and all their needs. As well as the actual camera operator.(They are amongst the highest paid on set. Sometimes they are locked in before the actors.) The job requires a lot of physical stability and patience depending on their speciality. Then you have the FIRST AD. Very integral part of a shoot. They have one of the hardest jobs working with locations in order to make sure we can shoot this day or that day and what times. Whew! Not to mention handling all the personalities on set. We have an amazing FIRST AD on â€œALICEâ€ â¤ï¸And the GRIPS! We can never forget the grips. On the first day of â€œALICEâ€ I got reconnected with the same Key Grip that I worked with on â€œAkeelah and The Beeâ€ and â€œThe Longshotsâ€. They are the ones that essentially set up everything! They are a huge back bone on a onset production. Thereâ€™s also KRAFTY! KRAFTY makes food and keeps snacks around all day on set and ensure that we eat while we work as sometimes we donâ€™t get to stop to eat. (Outside of one lunch)Anyhow! There are so many more from costumes, to electrics, to hair and makeup, to transpo, to locations, to PROPS(not to be confused with Art Department because props handles everything an actor TOUCHES). I say that to say, the actors are not the coolest on most sets. Itâ€™s always THE CREW!

MY DIRECTOR! @krystinverlinden.kvl, you are absolutely amazing. We are embarking on our last week and I canâ€™t tell you how amazing this shoot has been for me. I had to touch some of the saddest parts of my soul and I thank you for being gentle the entire way through. Krystin comes from a unique background and strong women! Her grandmother and cousin were members of the Black Panther Party in Oakland. She also wrote â€œALICEâ€ and is one of the strongest women Iâ€™ve ever met! I feel like we will be vibinâ€™ for years to come. â€œALICEâ€ is special Krystin, just like you! Happy last week.

"How do you deal with anxiety?" I've been asked this question countless times throughout the years, yet my answer is always the same. If I feel anxiety building out of nowhere, I literally put on my shoes, lock the door, and WALK. You don't need a set route or speed; flow through it. My best advice is to walk to do an errand - or have a destination in mind that you'd need to go to regardless. Moving through the physical body is incredibly cleansing, especially if you've felt trapped in your mind. If you walked instead of drove a car to the grocery store every day, imagine how much you'd be reducing your carbon footprint. And beyond that, how much stronger and more empowered you would feel in your shoes- which I have to give words of love and respect to @avrelife for. Thank you for making the most mind-blowingly sustainable exercise gear- and these gorgeous sneakers. When in doubt, walk it out :)

No Better YouIf you are new to my page, welcome! My name is Vanessa and I was on @bachelorabc a few years ago. During my hometown date, I went to visit my students at @galileoadultcentre  As a special education teacher, I wanted to give my students visibility and let the world see their ABILITIES.This time last year, I was surrounded by my closest friends who helped my non-profit @nobetteryou win $25,000 at a @hudsonsbay gift wrapping contest. Long story short, I started a non-profit called No Better You while my season was airing. If you are a teacher or parent, you understand the need to have access to resources, especially in the special education community. No Better You's mission is to help schools with special education programs build and have access to sensory rooms! Since 2017, we've raised $150,000 and helped 4 schools in Montreal build their very own sensory room.A sensory room is a therapeutic space designed to promote a calming and soothing experience. It relieves stress, facilitates communication and social interaction, increases focus and attention, promotes mental and physical relaxation and provides a safe place for students to explore and interact with their environment.After speaking and visiting a few schools in and around Toronto, No Better You selected @aptustreatmentcentre as the recipient of the $25,000! caption: Celebrating my body today, I have been upset at it lately, upset it didnâ€™t let me have a baby with the love of my life, upset for all the pain I go through every day, upset for not letting me living a life pain free. I felt resentful to it, angry. I always took my body as a machine that should work, listen to me, I pushed it over the limits, I didnâ€™t listened to its tiredness, I didnâ€™t listen to the pain. My body is a little broken, a little sick, itâ€™s not the perfect one, it doesnâ€™t work as I wish it would, but itâ€™s mine. I have to love it, I have to take care of it, I have to celebrate itâ€™s strength, itâ€™s weakness as I would for my soul. So today I am celebrating this imperfect body that is mine, at the end itâ€™s a fucking warrior, fighting everyday so I can feel better. When itâ€™s not about illness, itâ€™s about weight, shapes, we tend to hate on our bodies so easily instead of cherishing it. I donâ€™t want to take it for granted anymore. Have a nice day everyone, letâ€™s love ourselves a bit more.

Endo life. Thinking of all women, men who struggles with fertility, thinking of the ones who decided not to have kids and are constantly judged, pressured. Itâ€™s been over year since I am receiving message asking me when I will get pregnant, what I am waiting for. EVERY SINGLE DAY. I cannot gain weight, I cannot be bloated, I cannot make a step without having this question coming over and over again. You remember my post in April ? I gain weight and the numbers of message concerning a potential pregnancy were so intense I had to explain myself publicly, I was not pregnant, I gained weight. While I was receiving this tsunami of pregnancy questions I was struggling privately with fertility. Today I am asking for these questions to stop, not only for me, but for all of us.  For the ones who donâ€™t want children and are pressured every day, the ones who didnâ€™t make up theirs minds yet, the ones that like me would love to but are struggling.  These messages even genuine can hurt. Itâ€™s painful. I also want to thank everyone who sent me messages today, I am reading them with tears in my eyes, I feel extremely vulnerable speaking out loud of something so close to my intimacy, something so painful. The more I am reading your messages, the more I am convinced of the need and urge to speak louder. I also want to thank the ones that are sharing with me messages hope, I am not a mother yet, but I am a auntie, a friend, a wife, an entrepreneur, a superwoman, and I wonâ€™t let my struggles define me. Neither will you. Stronger together â¤ï¸

You ğŸ–¤ grateful to have my husband @riccardopozzoli by my side. A man that since I have been diagnosed keep getting informed online about endometriosis, keeps trying to calm my symptoms in all the way possible, grateful to have someone that I can let go with. A man that yesterday told me, after I was speaking about how infertility affect my feelings about my own femininity and sensuality, replied that I am the most gorgeous sexiest women alive, and he is more proud than ever to be next to me. Someone that hold my hand when I need it, that shares the pain and the weight of things, that take it out of my chest as much as he can. That spends times calling and writing to doctors for me, when I donâ€™t feel like I have the strength to do so. Someone that gets it, that wants to learn more, and that support me but mostly us, women. We need more of this, we need our brothers, uncles, friends to speak about our matters and to join us to have equal treatment. Equal treatment at work, in life and also in health. Feminism is a necessity; not an option.

Femininity, fertility... itâ€™s such a latent thing, we grew and live playing with baby toys, playing at being a mum when we are just 4. Infertility and femininity, how do you define that ? Somehow it makes you feel less of woman, because you are not able to nurture Life. Without even speaking about the social pressure right after getting married â€œ when is the baby for?â€ â€œStill not pregnant ?â€. Also how we treat women who decide not to become mothers because they donâ€™t want to, they way they are treated as if something was wrong with them. My struggles with fertility, my endo belly, my deception growing, the pain each month that comes with period, the shame, because yes even tho you try hard you feel ashamed. Ashamed because no one speak about this, you have to carry within yourself your pain, the stigma of the society and this terrible, deep silence. Speaking about this publicly, itâ€™s challenging. Thatâ€™s exactly because I hesitated and somehow felt ashamed, that I decided to speak even louder, because no one should be ashamed of this. Women should know about their uterus, information should be shared about what is touching our intimacy, we need to have this discussion openly so our intimate health matters becomes a priority, for the research, for the diagnostic, the cures. I am 30, when I think that I will have an ovary taken off soon, it gives me nausea, imagine... if we were telling to men we will be cutting off their balls ? We would have a cure already ! So letâ€™s speak louder ! Letâ€™s liberate the information, letâ€™s free the speech, and blow away the stigmas. I will continue to speak up, I will take it in even if itâ€™s hurting but I will never let this define me. To all the women that are going trough this, you are fucking warrior, you have all my respect and admiration, you are not alone. Stronger together. Bonne nuit.

caption: Those who know me know that I love a good coat. As I prepare to move Iâ€™m going through my endless racks of clothes trying to cull down to the essentials and those pieces with the most vibrant memories attached.In the process I find my greatest attachments are to my coats and I must admit my bags. Everything else seems much easier to recycle, donate or sell.My coats comfort and warm me like a much needed hug. They are my signature when fashion week comes in February. My bags seem to contain all my little fantasies, notebooks, pens and other objects that give hints of my current pursuits. The coat I wear is a country coat. Plaid with a fringe like the car blankets my mother threw in the station wagon for a long trip. This coat is my escort from here to there and will gather new memories as it does. The perfect companion for a new journey.Where do your clothes take you?

So much had happened in 2020 that I wanted to reflect and dream and consider a new way. I have changed immensely this year and through my own growth I have ultimately decided to officially retire NAKED. After much soul searching, and truthfully a few business snafus, I decided to honor myself and my new vision in the podcast space. There are a gazillion podcasts, but I have always prided myself on the uniqueness my guests and I bring to the table. Authenticity, soul, an ability to connect in a meaningful way. Iâ€™ll be damned - this pandemic has grabbed ahold of us. All of us. Life just isnâ€™t the same. So why do the same?Â Â I feel pulled to put out something new and different. To birth something else. Something even better! And so thatâ€™s what Iâ€™ve done. While I canâ€™t announce yet what that is, I just wanted to say thank you from the bottom of my heart for your support, your patience, your devotion. I hope I can count on all of you to join me on this new journey soon. And in this moment I feel compelled to quote @glennondoyle: â€œDestructionÂ is essential toÂ construction. 2020 has been a challenging year for us all. We have shared so much devastation and last week, triggered by a betrayal that I didnâ€™t see coming I had a brief mental breakdown. As I sat alone on a hotel bed in what felt like the darkest time of my life I thought that someone had put a curse on me. I received 3 huge blows of bad news in one morning. The pain I felt was immeasurable. I cried alone for hours. Loneliness is a huge trigger for me and I had never felt more alone. Usually I would call my sister Bianca then work my way through my family but on this day I felt I couldnâ€™t burden them anymore. They worry so much about me and it doesnâ€™t feel fair. So I decided to call some of my best friends. I called Rita and I just cried. Immediately, without me saying a word she knew exactly what to say she spoke for a while and I just listened. She reminded me that I am not alone and that I am loved and valued. â€œYou will get through thisâ€ Then I called one of my oldest friends Victoria. Sheâ€™s a great person to call in a crisis because she donâ€™t panic or worry she just says the right things. I called my best friend Michael; He shows little to no emotion ever but heâ€™s a very practical person. Finally, I called my manager and dear friend Leisa, by this point I was less emotional; She told me that I am not cursed I am blessed and whatever has happened there will be a positive in those messages somewhere I just need to search for them.That was an important message. After those phone calls I felt so much better, so much stronger. I left the hotel and drove to my friend Rafaâ€™s house and spent a couple days with his beautiful family. They feel like my own family when Iâ€™m in LA so that was the perfect environment to heal. I booked a flight that weekend and flew home to my sister. Today, a week later. I feel great.Feelings swing in roundabouts. Up and down and thatâ€™s ok. Itâ€™s ok to feel pain and to feel sad. Do not let those feeling consume you. Remind yourself that you are loved and that you are important. I wanted to share that story with you all because the tools I used may be lifesaving. CALL SOMEONE. Do not suffer alone.
